HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 908
By Harris
A RESOLUTION to commemorate March 4, 2026, as HPV
Awareness Day in Tennessee.
WHEREAS, human papillomavirus (HPV), a common virus that affects nearly everyone,
can lead to six types of cancer; nearly every U.S. citizen will contract the virus at some point in
his or her life; and
WHEREAS, oropharyngeal and cervical cancers are the two most prevalent HPV-
associated cancers in the U.S.; and
WHEREAS, the incidence rates of oropharyngeal and cervical cancers and of HPV
cancers overall are higher in Tennessee than the national averages; and
WHEREAS, a safe, highly effective, and long-lasting vaccination against HPV has been
recommended in the U.S. since 2006; this vaccination protects against ninety percent of HPV
cancers and is widely available; and
WHEREAS, HPV vaccination is recommended for all people nine to twenty-six years of
age and for some people twenty-seven to forty-five years of age who were not vaccinated as
children; and
WHEREAS, on-time HPV vaccination is routinely recommended at ages nine to twelve
years for optimal protection against HPV cancers as an adult; and
WHEREAS, while Tennessee has steadily increased the percentage of citizens having
received routinely recommended HPV vaccination, HPV vaccination coverage statewide
continues to lag; and
WHEREAS, the HPV Cancer Prevention Program of St. Jude Children's Research
Hospital is focused on galvanizing existing successful HPV cancer prevention efforts and
introducing new ones in support of increasing HPV vaccination and reducing HPV cancer cases
HJR0908
012784
- 1 -

and deaths across Memphis, the State of Tennessee, the Southeastern U.S., and nationally;
and
WHEREAS, to that end, the St. Jude HPV Cancer Prevention Program has formed the
HPV Vaccination Roundtable of the Southeast, which is inclusive of Tennessee medical and
public health professionals, to address low HPV vaccination coverage and high rates of HPV
cancers; and
WHEREAS, the international HPV Awareness Day campaign, Ask about HPV, is a key
initiative of the International Papillomavirus Society and its partners, including St. Jude
Children's Research Hospital; and
WHEREAS, this campaign aims to increase public awareness of the virus as part of its
mission to improve understanding of HPV and the importance of prevention, screening,
diagnosis, and treatment of papillomavirus-related diseases; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that March 4, 2026, is commemorated as HPV Awareness Day in Tennessee
to raise public awareness about HPV vaccinations and other HPV cancer prevention measures.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
